post_text: This week we also completed blind contour study while directly observing our hands. These blind contour and modified contours studies are exercises that allow students to observe, not simply just look at subject matter. A very successful week of engagement!!

post_text: We've been busy learning how to observe not just look at objects. We began with our blind contour are studies which is a direct unedited drawing that aligns the eyes movement around the object with the graphite. The purpose of this art exercise is not to create beautiful art work but it is an exercise that will lead to heightened observational awareness in the coming still life studies.

Water Valley Artist Society
June 16 at 5:57 PM ·

It is an honor and a privilege to share with you one of our Thesis Artist's Solo Exhibition's from our Graduate, Kelsey Humiston. Her exhibition includes works created solely from her thesis course studies. Please take time to enjoy her comprehensive and well thought out bodies of artwork as she confronts how we affect our world and how our world has been adapting to the changes that we cause using her art processes and content to lead the viewer through the journey. Kelsey's visual constructs connect well with her overall statement and year-long research. Kelsey has been an amazing student. Her willingness to take risks with her materials and through complex mixed media engagements has been inspiring. Kelsey has added a fearless complexity to the conversation concerning our plant and the issues of our modern world.

Click the link to view her virtual exhibition:)

https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/e/2PACX-1vSM55GxTfqKmLMHMPPnX7b0UOvr2IggpgzXguaswtY8o4OQHrNfY9M0URg60c5nbIfyJpvi2csIbmWh/pub?start=false&loop=false&delayms=10000

post_text:
It is an honor and a privilege to share with you one of our Thesis Artist's Solo Exhibition's from our Graduate, Aleena Sweeten. Her exhibition includes works created solely from her thesis course studies. Please take time to enjoy her comprehensive and well thought out arrangements of art processes venturing into a variety of psychological and metaphysical content elements contending with fear. Aleena's visual constructs connect well with her overall statement and year-long research. Aleena has been an amazing student adding her drive and creativity to our department for the past 3 years. Additionally she earned the Master Art Scholarship Award this past year, which is the top award for students in the WVAS art program.

https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/e/2PACX-1vSPt9dlZeeLwITYmb428qMZZacyI1iqD4vbdgdR5oEHOrGIZJACis2IZ420c6kQpkt08IM9UPVrID52/pub?start=true&loop=false&delayms=10000

post_text:
Art Studio/ Final Series: "ARCIMBOLDO & OUR DIGITAL PORTRAITURE AS NARRATIVE"

For my art student's final assignment of the year, they were to create a personal narrative to reveal a feeling based on their reflection or feeling concerning elements of a season, event, existential elements or time of day being studied, using Giuseppe Arcimboldo as our guide.

I gave my students the flexibility to choose what aspect they chose to study as long as they are able to visually connect it to their personal feeling or identity with relation to the subject matter they chose.

I asked my students to create 3 to 4 original “selfie” portraits using imagery to tell their personal story using the subject matter and assemblage of objects and filters to further form their personal narratives.

I hope you enjoy their final artistic discoveries.

Here's a study by Jaysen Gomez, Art 1

Here's a study by Canon Wiese, Art 1

WVAS Distance Studio Course work: I asked my artists to create an altered landscape using their phone, ipad, computer, or paper and art supplies. I wanted to have the students develop content and signification using objects or "digital stickers" to do so. Through this lesson I shared research about the surrealistic movement while also teaching a lesson about atmospheric perspective and the rules connected to this form of artistic study. Illusion of spatial elements are rendered in many forms... this time it's embedded in a landscape:)

post_text:
Distance Learning Project: I asked Art 1 and 2 students to use items around their homes to exaggerate still life object(s) either by making features of the object larger, smaller, or fragmented into multiples. I encouraged these students to draw the object in a way that is re-purposing the object by altering its scale and function. I also encouraged students to research surrealism and consider some of the visual content expressed within these works.

Here is a study by Canon Wiese.

post_text:
Distance Learning Project, "Seeing Past the Photo". Art 3 artists chose a personal photo in order to “See Past It”. Their challenge was to alter the meaning or memory of a personal photograph. I asked them to consider additions to the photo which could includes a person or object that they would want in the photo, or some elements that suggest a metaphysical presence, or objects or designs that suggest an internal feeling.

Here's a study by Kayle Chandler

post_text: Here are the winning entries for our annual group juried exhibition!!
text: Here are the winning entries for our annual group juried exhibition!!

post_text:
We persevered through the circumstances to create this online group exhibition, "Studio Musings". This is a collection of works from the Water Valley Artist Society of the Water Valley Independent School District to be juried by Professor Randy Hall of Angelo State University. This variety of works includes works from all high school art students in the program. Please share with others. This online exhibition is in place of the regular Coop Gallery showings we have downtown annually. A special thank you to Randy Hall and Shaydee Watson for their help with this exhibition. Their expertise and professionalism are always above and beyond.

https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1azOQ1MBnLqC0F14iJe0yNiaaOG-YG3q0jNGgaOAoZDM/edit?usp=drivesdk

post_text:
Art 4 Thesis Artist Profile: Kelsey Humiston
Kelsey has been working on a collection of illustrations which include paintings drawings and collage elements all connected to develop awareness of the viewer to man-made issues that affect our environment. Her focus is to take each diorama and create within it a system which is created by refuse or objects thrown away. She takes and develops sensitivity and empathy through her studies for those species which are now endangered. Humiston's drawings and paintings allow viewers to become sympathetic with their plight and the destruction of the beauty that is and once was. She will be continuing her study which will include an end-of-the-year thesis art exhibition and lecture.

All of the art students in the program are fine-tuning their observation skills by viewing the subject matter 100% of the time without looking at what they're drawing. :)!!

post_text: Many of my art students have been focused on contour drawing, specifically blind contour drawing. I am very impressed by their willingness to try new drawing methods in order to become a better observer of objects and details. Students are 100% engaged on the object and have 0% editing power during a blind contour study. They have to draw under the table while observing the object.The rationale behind blind contour studies is that it improves hand-eye coordination and the contour line becomes an accurate indicator of how the eye moves around and within the details of the subject being observed.

post_text:
Our first Art 4 thesis exhibition of the year is up and coming. Artist, Kawika Samaniego will be exhibiting his collection of artworks in the Wildcat Gallery located in the Administration Building. Mark your calendars! This exhibition questions the meaning of beauty while testing viewer preconceptions of how beauty is viewed. Please drop by and leave your response about the exhibition. The exhibition is open to Parents, Teachers, Students, Administrators, and Staff. "Aestheticism, The Meaning of Beauty" will run from March 20th through the 29th. Remember if you come to see the exhibition to check in at the HS Office before coming to the administration building. View the flyer for more information.

Hope to see you there! -Mr. Voss

post_text: Mason Lemons has won "Best of Show" honors at the "Silhouettes Combined" group exhibition at the Wildcat Gallery. As voted by his peers, Mason earned 57 total vote points. Capturing 2nd place was Carlee Sims for her mixed media collage, "Appearances". 3rd place honors go to Kelsey Humiston for her symbolist study entitled "Reflection" and the honorable mention award goes to Emma Rust for her mixed media collage combine "Blurred Lines." All votes are from Water Valley Artist Society members who currently attend Studio courses here at Water Valley.

post_text:
August 2, 2018
Dear Sue Mims,
I will always cherish our conversations about art and am thankful to have had the chance to know you. Your love and dedication to the students that made art at Water Valley Artist Society will ring in eternity. So thankful for all of your wisdom and the ways that you encouraged me as an art instructor. You will not be forgotten by me.

Chris Voss
Art Instructor, Adjunct Professor
Water Valley ISD, Angelo State University

Hello.....just wanted to share the supplies you'll need to provide if you are taking an Art Studio course during the 2018-19 school year. But don't miss out on one second of summer. Every bit counts!! Be ready, as I will be, for a great year of creativity!!

Best, Mr. Voss

Supply List...
Water Valley Artist Society Art Department List
Art Instructor: Mr. Voss

Essential
18 x 24 Newsprint Pad
9 x 12 Sketchbook/ Pad
Drawing Variety Set or Sketching Pencils 12 CT, Hard and Soft Leads Range 6H-6B
12 or 24 pk Colored Pencils (Scholar, Sargent or Prisma brands if possible)
Enclosed Prismacolor Pencil Sharpener
Found Objects (Per my request throughout the year)
3-5 White Erasers

Optional
Stretched Canvas (If Student Wishes for Independent Studies)
Prismacolor Water Color Pencil Set
Mixed media materials (for collage studies)
Zip Drive (for saving research and statements)

post_text: This was our Final Research Project and Print study for Art 3 : Art in Historical Context. Each student had to take a selfie, transfer it onto a linoleum plate, carving away either the negative or positive space using the subtractive method. This would leave a relief for printing multiple images using the same or a variety of colors. Each student had to do research on the Pop Art age of art and make the comparison to our contemporary culture, it's longing for self imagery as a commodity, and the connection our current culture has to the Pop Art commentary on consumerism and the craving for notoriety. Very proud of each of these artists and the way that they conducted themselves in the studio all year round.

post_text: Every year my Art HS students study the figure through figure drawing. This 4 week study includes excercises such as finding the motif, gesture to study movement, landmarking within the anatomical structure to study measurements, anatomical skeletal and superficial muscle group studies. Attached are just a few of the many improved studies. Each image shows the students first study next to their finals.
text: Every year my Art HS students study the figure through figure drawing. This 4 week study includes excercises such as finding the motif, gesture to study movement, landmarking within the anatomical structure to study measurements, anatomical skeletal and superficial muscle group studies. Attached are just a few of the many improved studies. Each image shows the students first study next to their finals.
